sec.p:
To compare between sessions, the mean signal intensity (S) from each session (N) was normalized by subtracting the mean signal intensity in the baseline sessions (b¯)\begin{document}$(\bar{b})$\end{document}, and dividing by the standard deviation of the baseline σb to give a t score for each session, as described in Equation (1):
tN=SN−b¯σb \begin{document}$$\displaystyle t_{N}=\frac{S_{N}-\bar{b}}{\sigma_{b}}$$\end{document}
Data were analyzed using custom scripts written in the MATLAB environment (R2020a, MathWorks). Mean signal intensity in the proximal to distal z slices was smoothed with a moving window of five z slices. Z slice windows were tested against their respective baseline sessions. A total of nine scans spanning sessions prior to and immediately following the virus injections contributed towards the baseline period for the left and right arms of both animals. All statistical tests were performed using custom MATLAB scripts. The Benjamini-Hochberg procedure was performed to correct for multiple comparisons[30].
